1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:06,400
You are programmed to always chase 
price, always one step behind the market. 

2
00:00:06,400 --> 00:00:12,760
That’s because the big players hunt liquidity, 
creating the moves others try to follow! 

3
00:00:12,760 --> 00:00:18,382
Today I'll teach you how to spot and 
trade liquidity, just like the pros!
  

4
00:00:18,382 --> 00:00:19,320
What is liquidity?
When you first started  

5
00:00:19,320 --> 00:00:26,320
trading, you probably learned about support and 
resistance, chart patterns, and other basic stuff. 

6
00:00:26,320 --> 00:00:33,280
Many brokers even offer free education on these 
topics. But why? It's not just to be nice!
  

7
00:00:33,280 --> 00:00:37,080
They want lots of traders 
using the same strategies. 

8
00:00:37,080 --> 00:00:41,800
Because this creates predictable 
liquidity, that can be exploited. 

9
00:00:41,800 --> 00:00:48,120
Think about it. If most traders are using 
the same methods, it's easy for big banks and  

10
00:00:48,120 --> 00:00:53,400
institutions to predict what they'll do. 
 
They can use this knowledge to move the  

11
00:00:53,400 --> 00:00:58,520
market in ways that benefit them.
It's like setting up dominos. Once  

12
00:00:58,520 --> 00:01:03,560
they're all lined up, it just takes 
a little push to create a big effect. 

13
00:01:03,560 --> 00:01:09,600
This is liquidity! In its simplest form, 
liquidity refers to the orders or money  

14
00:01:09,600 --> 00:01:13,120
present in the market.
 
Market prices move based  

15
00:01:13,120 --> 00:01:19,160
on the flow of buy and sell orders.
More buying pressure pushes prices up,  

16
00:01:19,160 --> 00:01:25,240
while more selling pressure pushes prices down.
For substantial price movements to occur,  

17
00:01:25,240 --> 00:01:32,360
the market needs to interact with areas of high 
order concentration, also known as liquidity.
  

18
00:01:32,360 --> 00:01:37,520
So liquidity means all the buy and 
sell orders waiting to be filled. 

19
00:01:37,520 --> 00:01:42,880
Now, here's the interesting part - if there 
isn't enough liquidity, the big players,  

20
00:01:42,880 --> 00:01:47,680
the smart money, will create it.
For big traders, like banks or  

21
00:01:47,680 --> 00:01:52,960
hedge funds, liquidity is critical. 
 
They deal with large amounts of money. 

22
00:01:52,960 --> 00:01:58,120
In less liquid markets, their big 
trades can push prices around a lot. 

23
00:01:58,120 --> 00:02:02,640
This makes it hard for them to 
buy or sell without losing money. 

24
00:02:02,640 --> 00:02:09,320
Now, if you understand where liquidity sits, you 
can identify magnet areas, those price levels that  

25
00:02:09,320 --> 00:02:12,000
attract price movement.  
 
What are liquidity pools 

26
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:18,360
Your main task is to find liquidity pools.
Liquidity pools are like busy trading spots  

27
00:02:18,360 --> 00:02:20,600
in the market.
They're areas  

28
00:02:20,600 --> 00:02:27,000
where lots of buy and sell orders gather.
And they form at key price levels. These could  

29
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:34,600
be previous highs or lows, round numbers or other 
important points. We’ll talk about these later.
  

30
00:02:34,600 --> 00:02:42,040
Now, traders often place their orders at these 
levels, creating a cluster of potential trades. 

31
00:02:42,040 --> 00:02:48,040
There are different types of liquidity pools:
Major liquidity pools, which form at the  

32
00:02:48,040 --> 00:02:53,040
highs and lows of longer timeframes.
These are big, important levels that  

33
00:02:53,040 --> 00:02:59,160
many traders watch. You might see them on 
weekly, monthly, or even yearly charts.
  

34
00:02:59,160 --> 00:03:06,040
Medium liquidity pools, that show up on shorter 
timeframes, like 1-hour charts. These are still  

35
00:03:06,040 --> 00:03:13,400
significant, but not as big as the major pools.
 
Minor liquidity pools appear on very short  

36
00:03:13,400 --> 00:03:19,400
timeframes, like 1-minute or 5-minute 
charts. These are smaller and might  

37
00:03:19,400 --> 00:03:25,680
only matter for very short-term traders.
 
 
Liquidity pools work by attracting price. 

38
00:03:25,680 --> 00:03:29,760
When price approaches a liquidity 
pool, a few things can happen. 

39
00:03:30,360 --> 00:03:35,240
It might reverse, as lots of 
orders get filled at that level. 

40
00:03:35,240 --> 00:03:41,760
Or it might pause there before continuing.
Sometimes, it might even break through quickly,  

41
00:03:41,760 --> 00:03:45,960
if there's enough momentum.
 
And big players are constantly  

42
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:51,840
trying to "hunt" these liquidity pools.
They often push price to these levels, to trigger  

43
00:03:51,840 --> 00:03:55,560
a bunch of orders, causing a sharp move.
 
How to identify liquidity zones 

44
00:03:55,560 --> 00:04:01,680
So liquidity zones are key areas on a chart where 
smart money players often target, to protect  

45
00:04:01,680 --> 00:04:08,440
their positions and to trap retail traders.
These zones act like magnets for price, drawing  

46
00:04:08,440 --> 00:04:15,200
it in, and often causing significant moves.
So let's talk about each type of liquidity zone,  

47
00:04:15,200 --> 00:04:23,200
and how smart money uses them to their advantage.
 
First area is around structural highs and lows.  

48
00:04:23,200 --> 00:04:28,960
These are major turning points in price action.
The the peaks and valleys you see on a chart,  

49
00:04:28,960 --> 00:04:33,680
that stand out from the rest.
Smart money loves these spots  

50
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:39,200
because they know traders often place 
their stop losses just beyond them.
  

51
00:04:39,200 --> 00:04:45,320
Let's say we have a strong uptrend, with 
a series of higher highs and higher lows. 

52
00:04:45,320 --> 00:04:52,120
Traders often jump on this trend, placing 
their stops just below the most recent low. 

53
00:04:52,120 --> 00:04:58,000
And smart money knows this. They often 
push the price down, breaking that low  

54
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:03,440
and triggering all those stop losses.
This flood of sell orders drives the  

55
00:05:03,440 --> 00:05:09,880
price down further, often before smart 
money steps in to buy, at a discount.
  

56
00:05:09,880 --> 00:05:16,040
The same happens in downtrends. Retail 
shorts place their stops above recent highs. 

57
00:05:16,040 --> 00:05:22,040
Smart money spike the price up, hit those 
stops, then drive the price back down. 

58
00:05:22,040 --> 00:05:26,600
To spot these zones, look for clear 
swing highs and lows on your charts. 

59
00:05:26,600 --> 00:05:31,760
The more obvious they are, the more 
likely they are to attract attention. 
  

60
00:05:31,760 --> 00:05:37,840
Trend lines are another favorite tool of traders. 
The diagonal lines that connect a series of  

61
00:05:37,840 --> 00:05:45,920
lows in an uptrend, or highs in a downtrend.
They're simple to draw and easy to understand,  

62
00:05:45,920 --> 00:05:52,680
which is why so many traders rely on them.
 
Big players often target these trend lines,  

63
00:05:52,680 --> 00:05:57,480
especially long-standing ones.
They know that many traders will have  

64
00:05:57,480 --> 00:06:03,880
stop losses placed just beyond these lines.
By breaking a significant trend line,  

65
00:06:03,880 --> 00:06:09,920
they can trigger a cascade of orders.
 
For instance, in a long-standing uptrend,  

66
00:06:09,920 --> 00:06:14,960
many traders will be long with their 
stops just below the trend line. 

67
00:06:14,960 --> 00:06:18,880
Smart money might push the 
price down to break this line. 

68
00:06:18,880 --> 00:06:26,400
As stops are hit, more sell orders flood in. 
Smart money can then step in, and buy at lower  

69
00:06:26,400 --> 00:06:32,520
prices before resuming the uptrend.
 
Equal highs and lows, also known as  

70
00:06:32,520 --> 00:06:37,960
double tops and double bottoms, 
are also exploited by smart money. 

71
00:06:37,960 --> 00:06:45,200
These patterns form when price reaches the same 
level twice, creating a potential reversal point. 

72
00:06:45,200 --> 00:06:50,520
Traders often see these patterns and 
place their trades accordingly. 
  

73
00:06:50,520 --> 00:06:56,240
For a double top, they might go short, 
with a stop just above the equal highs. 

74
00:06:56,240 --> 00:07:02,320
For a double bottom, they might go long, 
with a stop just below the equal lows. 

75
00:07:02,320 --> 00:07:08,280
Smart money knows this and often pushes the 
price just beyond these levels to trigger  

76
00:07:08,280 --> 00:07:13,120
stop losses, before reversing.
This creates a liquidity pool  

77
00:07:13,120 --> 00:07:19,080
that they can use to their advantage.
 
Trading sessions, particularly the Asian,  

78
00:07:19,080 --> 00:07:24,760
London, and New York sessions, often 
create their own ranges. These ranges  

79
00:07:24,760 --> 00:07:29,520
can become significant liquidity zones, 
especially at their highs and lows. 

80
00:07:30,360 --> 00:07:35,520
Big players often target the sessions’ highs 
and lows, because they know many traders use  

81
00:07:35,520 --> 00:07:41,800
them for entries and stop placements. 
 
For example, many traders use the Asian  

82
00:07:41,800 --> 00:07:49,160
session range as a guide for the London session.
They might place buy orders above the Asian high,  

83
00:07:49,160 --> 00:07:54,880
and sell orders below the Asian low.
Smart money might push the price just  

84
00:07:54,880 --> 00:08:01,360
beyond these levels to trigger these orders, 
creating liquidity that they can trade against. 

85
00:08:01,360 --> 00:08:07,560
They might spike the price above the Asian high, 
triggering buy orders, only to sell into this  

86
00:08:07,560 --> 00:08:14,280
liquidity, and push the price back down.
 
The previous day's high and low are other  

87
00:08:14,280 --> 00:08:20,200
significant levels that many traders watch.
They often serve as support and resistance  

88
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:25,440
levels for the current day's trading.
Again, the big boys know this, and frequently  

89
00:08:25,440 --> 00:08:29,760
target these levels.
 
For instance, many traders place  

90
00:08:29,760 --> 00:08:36,200
buy orders just above the previous day's high, 
expecting the upward momentum to continue. 

91
00:08:36,200 --> 00:08:42,880
Smart money will push the price up to trigger 
these orders, creating a pool of liquidity. 

92
00:08:42,880 --> 00:08:49,040
They can then sell into this liquidity, 
potentially reversing the price direction.
  

93
00:08:49,040 --> 00:08:54,000
The previous week's high and low also 
attract a lot of attention. You might  

94
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:59,480
not even know where those levels are.
These levels often act as key support  

95
00:08:59,480 --> 00:09:05,840
and resistance on higher timeframes.
And smart money often exploit these levels,  

96
00:09:05,840 --> 00:09:09,840
knowing that many swing traders 
and position traders use them  

97
00:09:09,840 --> 00:09:16,720
for stop placement and entry orders. 
 
For example, in a downtrend, many traders  

98
00:09:16,720 --> 00:09:22,920
might place sell orders below the previous 
week's low, expecting the trend to continue. 

99
00:09:22,920 --> 00:09:27,320
Smart money often push the price 
down to trigger these orders,  

100
00:09:27,320 --> 00:09:34,360
creating a liquidity pool they can buy into.
 
Supply and demand zones are other liquidity  

101
00:09:34,360 --> 00:09:40,640
zones. These are areas where price has 
shown significant rejection in the past. 

102
00:09:40,640 --> 00:09:46,000
And these zones are prime targets 
for smart money manipulation. 

103
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:50,400
Smart money know many traders 
place their orders around them. 
  

104
00:09:50,400 --> 00:09:57,720
For example, many traders might place buy orders 
at a strong demand zone. Smart money might  

105
00:09:57,720 --> 00:10:04,040
push the price into this zone, triggering 
these buy orders and creating liquidity. 

106
00:10:04,040 --> 00:10:09,720
They can then potentially sell into this 
liquidity, driving the price even lower. 

107
00:10:09,720 --> 00:10:13,680
That’s why you see so many demand 
zones that should work, in theory,  

108
00:10:13,680 --> 00:10:17,800
but in reality, they fail.
 
The same happens with supply  

109
00:10:17,800 --> 00:10:24,360
zones. Traders often place sell orders 
at these levels, expecting price to drop. 

110
00:10:24,360 --> 00:10:29,320
Smart money might spike the price into the 
supply zone, triggering these sell orders,  

111
00:10:30,280 --> 00:10:35,680
then buy into this liquidity to 
potentially drive the price higher.
  

112
00:10:35,680 --> 00:10:40,200
Fair Value Gaps (FVGs) are also 
targeted. These are areas on the  

113
00:10:40,200 --> 00:10:46,200
chart where price has moved rapidly.
These gaps often act as magnets for  

114
00:10:46,200 --> 00:10:53,560
price, drawing it back to "fill" the gap.
Smart money often uses these gaps as targets. 
  

115
00:10:53,560 --> 00:10:58,760
For example, if there's a bullish Fair 
Value Gaps, below the current price,  

116
00:10:58,760 --> 00:11:06,480
many traders might place buy orders in this area, 
expecting price to come back and fill the gap. 

117
00:11:06,480 --> 00:11:11,240
Smart money might push the price down 
through this level, triggering these  

118
00:11:11,240 --> 00:11:16,560
buy orders and creating liquidity. 
 
The same happens with bearish Fair  

119
00:11:16,560 --> 00:11:22,280
Value Gaps, above the current price.
Traders often place sell orders in these  

120
00:11:22,280 --> 00:11:29,440
areas. Smart money might spike the price up 
through the gap, triggering these sell orders. 

121
00:11:29,440 --> 00:11:36,040
That’s why maybe 90% of fair value gaps 
fail. But that’s a topic for another video!
  

122
00:11:36,040 --> 00:11:43,240
Round numbers, ending in zero or double zeros, are 
psychologically significant levels that attract a  

123
00:11:43,240 --> 00:11:46,160
lot of attention from traders.
These levels are prime  

124
00:11:46,160 --> 00:11:51,640
targets for smart money manipulation.
Smart money knows that many retail traders  

125
00:11:51,640 --> 00:11:57,360
place their orders around these round numbers.
Many traders might place buy orders just above  

126
00:11:57,360 --> 00:12:04,080
a round number, or sell orders just below it.
The big boys often push the price to these  

127
00:12:04,080 --> 00:12:09,720
levels to trigger these orders, creating 
liquidity that they can trade against.
  

128
00:12:09,720 --> 00:12:14,000
For instance, if there's a round 
number at the 50 dollar level,  

129
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:21,400
many traders might place buy orders slightly above 
it, expecting the price to rise above this level. 

130
00:12:21,400 --> 00:12:28,680
The big boys might push the price up, to trigger 
these buy orders, creating a pool of liquidity. 

131
00:12:28,680 --> 00:12:34,640
They can then potentially sell into this 
liquidity, driving the price back down. 

132
00:12:34,640 --> 00:12:39,960
Understanding all these liquidity zones, 
and how smart money targets them is key. 

133
00:12:39,960 --> 00:12:46,120
It helps you avoid common traps. 
 
As you practice, you'll start to see patterns. 

134
00:12:46,120 --> 00:12:52,640
You might notice that price often reverses 
after taking out a previous high or low. 

135
00:12:52,640 --> 00:12:58,360
Or you might see that certain levels 
keep causing price to pause or reverse. 
  

136
00:12:58,360 --> 00:13:02,960
And please, don't just draw 
liquidity zones all over your chart. 

137
00:13:02,960 --> 00:13:09,200
Focus on the most important ones. Too many 
zones can make your analysis confusing.
  

138
00:13:09,200 --> 00:13:14,840
Also, pay attention to how price reacts 
when it reaches a liquidity zone. 

139
00:13:14,840 --> 00:13:21,520
Does it reverse sharply? Does it pause and 
then continue? Or does it blow right through? 

140
00:13:21,520 --> 00:13:27,400
This can give you clues about the strength 
of the move, and what might happen next.
  

141
00:13:27,400 --> 00:13:33,080
You might notice that certain types of zones 
work better in certain market conditions,  

142
00:13:33,080 --> 00:13:39,560
or for certain currency pairs or stocks.
This is where keeping a detailed trading journal  

143
00:13:39,560 --> 00:13:47,060
with your findings, can be incredibly valuable, 
allowing you to refine your strategy over time.
  

144
00:13:47,060 --> 00:13:50,120
Liquidity inducement
Now let’s talk about liquidity inducement. 

145
00:13:50,120 --> 00:13:57,400
Inducement is about creating situations that make 
other traders want to trade, at certain levels. 

146
00:13:57,400 --> 00:14:02,720
This creates available liquidity for bigger 
players to use, when they want to enter  

147
00:14:02,720 --> 00:14:06,800
or exit their positions.
 
To understand this better,  

148
00:14:06,800 --> 00:14:13,680
let's look at how the market is structured.
When we look at charts, we see highs and lows. 

149
00:14:13,680 --> 00:14:19,320
Above these highs, we assume there's 
buy-side liquidity, and below the lows,  

150
00:14:19,320 --> 00:14:25,080
we assume there's sell-side liquidity.
 
Buy-side liquidity is all the liquidity  

151
00:14:25,080 --> 00:14:33,280
that buyers will use, created mainly by stop loss 
orders of sellers, and buy stop orders of buyers. 

152
00:14:33,280 --> 00:14:40,040
In a bullish market, price often uses buy-side 
liquidity to fuel the next upward move. 

153
00:14:40,040 --> 00:14:46,120
To have a big bullish move, the market needs 
sell orders to generate more liquidity. 

154
00:14:46,120 --> 00:14:53,080
Also, the buy orders from stop losses of sellers 
generate more buy orders, which is why you often  

155
00:14:53,080 --> 00:14:59,480
see a surge in buying when price breaks out.
 
Sell-side liquidity is the opposite.  

156
00:14:59,480 --> 00:15:04,800
It's the liquidity that sellers will use, 
created mainly by stop loss orders of  

157
00:15:04,800 --> 00:15:10,800
buyers and sell stop orders of sellers.
Imagine you see a double bottom on your  

158
00:15:10,800 --> 00:15:16,480
chart. This is when price hits the same 
low point twice, forming a support level. 

159
00:15:16,480 --> 00:15:22,760
Many traders might want to buy at this support 
level. Now, think about where these traders  

160
00:15:22,760 --> 00:15:26,640
would put their stop losses.
They'd likely put them just  

161
00:15:26,640 --> 00:15:32,760
below the lows. This creates a pool of 
sell-side liquidity below the lows.
  

162
00:15:32,760 --> 00:15:36,960
This is important because big 
players need this liquidity. 

163
00:15:36,960 --> 00:15:42,840
They can't just jump into the market with huge 
orders - that would cause wild price swings,  

164
00:15:42,840 --> 00:15:46,920
and could work against them.
Instead, they use liquidity  

165
00:15:46,920 --> 00:15:52,680
inducement to their advantage.
 
These big players create patterns or situations  

166
00:15:52,680 --> 00:15:58,920
in the market, that encourage other traders 
to place their orders in predictable spots. 

167
00:15:59,440 --> 00:16:03,960
This builds up pools of liquidity, 
that the big players can then use  

168
00:16:03,960 --> 00:16:09,560
to enter or exit their positions.
Now, before we continue, let us know  

169
00:16:09,560 --> 00:16:15,720
in the comments what topics you’d like us to 
cover! And please drop us a like to help us  

170
00:16:15,720 --> 00:16:18,240
with Youtube algorithm.
 
Liquidity sweeps 

171
00:16:18,240 --> 00:16:23,640
Now let's talk about how big players 
use this liquidity. They often create  

172
00:16:23,640 --> 00:16:28,320
what's called a "liquidity sweep".
It's when big players in the market,  

173
00:16:28,320 --> 00:16:34,560
try to take advantage of areas where 
there's a lot of buy or sell orders waiting. 

174
00:16:34,560 --> 00:16:39,680
These areas are like pools of money 
just sitting there, ready to be used.
  

175
00:16:39,680 --> 00:16:45,880
For instance, if there's a strong support level 
with many stop losses just below it, price might  

176
00:16:45,880 --> 00:16:52,600
sweep down to hit those stops before reversing.
This action "sweeps" the liquidity, letting  

177
00:16:52,600 --> 00:16:57,640
larger players fill their orders.
 
Knowing about liquidity sweeps can  

178
00:16:57,640 --> 00:17:01,720
help you in two main ways.
First, you can look for where  

179
00:17:01,720 --> 00:17:08,360
sweeps have already happened, as this might 
show where big players have been active. 

180
00:17:08,360 --> 00:17:12,640
Second, you can use this knowledge 
to guess future moves, by spotting  

181
00:17:12,640 --> 00:17:18,120
where available liquidity might be.
 
One way to trade these liquidity sweeps,  

182
00:17:18,120 --> 00:17:23,600
is by identifying "the inducement" 
before a potential zone of interest. 

183
00:17:23,600 --> 00:17:28,320
This is where price action might 
encourage traders to enter positions,  

184
00:17:28,320 --> 00:17:34,520
creating more liquidity for a potential move.
 
For example, if you're looking at a possible  

185
00:17:34,520 --> 00:17:40,840
buy zone, you might see price dip below 
a previous low before the main move up. 

186
00:17:40,840 --> 00:17:46,040
This dip could make sellers enter 
short positions or exit longs,  

187
00:17:46,040 --> 00:17:52,640
creating liquidity that larger players 
can use to enter their long positions.
 

188
00:17:52,640 --> 00:17:53,430
liquidity and market structure

189
00:17:53,430 --> 00:17:57,040
Liquidity goes hand in hand with market structure. 

190
00:17:57,040 --> 00:18:03,600
Market structure refers to the overall pattern 
of price movement. It's about identifying trends,  

191
00:18:03,600 --> 00:18:09,920
key levels, and the flow of the market.
Liquidity is about where buying and selling  

192
00:18:09,920 --> 00:18:15,760
activity clusters. These two concepts 
work together to shape market behavior 
  

193
00:18:15,760 --> 00:18:19,160
Here's how they interact.
First, areas of high liquidity  

194
00:18:19,160 --> 00:18:24,400
often become key points in the market structure.
For example, a level with lots of buy orders  

195
00:18:24,400 --> 00:18:29,800
might become a strong support level.
If price keeps bouncing off this level,  

196
00:18:29,800 --> 00:18:35,120
it becomes part of the market structure.
 
Key structural levels tend to attract  

197
00:18:35,120 --> 00:18:41,320
liquidity. Traders often place their 
orders around important structural points,  

198
00:18:41,320 --> 00:18:47,760
like trend lines or previous highs and lows.
This creates a feedback loop where structure  

199
00:18:47,760 --> 00:18:53,880
and liquidity reinforce each other.
 
Breaks in structure can drain liquidity.  

200
00:18:53,880 --> 00:19:00,640
When price breaks through a key structural level, 
it often leads to a surge in trading activity. 

201
00:19:00,640 --> 00:19:08,400
This can temporarily drain liquidity from other 
areas as traders rush to adjust their positions
  

202
00:19:08,400 --> 00:19:14,160
Liquidity flows with structure: in a 
strong trend, liquidity tends to cluster  

203
00:19:14,160 --> 00:19:18,800
in the direction of the trend.
For example, in an uptrend,  

204
00:19:18,800 --> 00:19:25,920
you might see more liquidity above the current 
price as traders anticipate further rises.
  

205
00:19:25,920 --> 00:19:30,920
Structure helps predict liquidity. 
By reading the market structure,  

206
00:19:30,920 --> 00:19:37,680
you can often predict where liquidity might be.
For instance, after a series of higher lows in  

207
00:19:37,680 --> 00:19:43,680
an uptrend, you can expect liquidity 
to gather below each of these lows.
  

208
00:19:43,680 --> 00:19:50,320
Liquidity confirms structure. Sometimes, the 
way price interacts with liquidity can confirm,  

209
00:19:50,320 --> 00:19:55,560
or deny the current market structure.
If price easily breaks through what  

210
00:19:55,560 --> 00:20:02,240
should be a liquidity-rich level, it might 
signal a change in the overall structure.
  

211
00:20:02,240 --> 00:20:09,400
Both liquidity and market structure guide price 
movement. Price often moves towards liquidity,  

212
00:20:09,400 --> 00:20:13,360
but within the constraints of 
the larger market structure. 

213
00:20:13,360 --> 00:20:18,920
And institutional activity links them. 
Big players in the market often use  

214
00:20:18,920 --> 00:20:24,680
their understanding of both liquidity 
and structure, to plan their trades. 
  

215
00:20:24,680 --> 00:20:30,960
Both liquidity and market structure change 
over time: just as market structure evolves,  

216
00:20:30,960 --> 00:20:36,880
so does the distribution of liquidity.
What was a key liquidity level last week  

217
00:20:36,880 --> 00:20:44,560
might not be as important now. So keeping track 
of both helps you stay in tune with the market.
  

218
00:20:44,560 --> 00:20:50,320
The interplay between liquidity and structure 
can help you spot truly important levels in the  

219
00:20:50,320 --> 00:20:57,840
market. Areas where structural levels align with 
high liquidity are often the most significant.
  

220
00:20:57,840 --> 00:21:02,440
In trading, we often talk about 
"market structure shifts". The  

221
00:21:02,440 --> 00:21:09,400
big changes in the overall trend of the market.
Inducement often plays a role in these shifts.
  

222
00:21:09,400 --> 00:21:14,800
For example, before a major trend change, 
you might see price action that looks  

223
00:21:14,800 --> 00:21:19,720
like it's continuing the old trend.
This can trick traders into entering  

224
00:21:19,720 --> 00:21:25,840
positions in the direction of the old trend, 
creating liquidity for the smart money to use  

225
00:21:25,840 --> 00:21:30,800
when reversing the market.
 
Also, liquidity inducement  

226
00:21:30,800 --> 00:21:35,720
is part of a larger market cycle.
The market typically goes through phases of  

227
00:21:35,720 --> 00:21:42,680
accumulation, markup, distribution, and markdown.
Liquidity inducement often occurs during the  

228
00:21:42,680 --> 00:21:50,000
accumulation and distribution phases, as smart 
money prepares for the next significant move.
  

229
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:57,080
During accumulation, for instance, you might see 
price action that looks choppy and directionless. 

230
00:21:57,080 --> 00:22:04,040
This can discourage retail traders and shake 
out weak hands, while smart money quietly builds  

231
00:22:04,040 --> 00:22:10,280
positions. The apparent lack of direction 
is itself a form of liquidity inducement,  

232
00:22:10,280 --> 00:22:15,800
creating opportunities for larger 
players to buy at favorable prices. 

233
00:22:15,800 --> 00:22:21,760
This is why it's crucial to look beyond 
just price action and consider volume,  

234
00:22:21,760 --> 00:22:27,851
momentum, and other factors that might 
indicate the true market dynamics.
 
  

235
00:22:27,851 --> 00:22:31,080
Liquidity inducement strategy
Liquidity inducement isn't something bad. 

236
00:22:31,080 --> 00:22:35,800
If you can spot it happening, you 
might find good trading signals. 

237
00:22:35,800 --> 00:22:40,520
For entries, look for areas 
where there's a lot of liquidity. 

238
00:22:40,520 --> 00:22:46,280
When the market is going up, look for 
buy entries just below recent lows. 

239
00:22:46,280 --> 00:22:51,520
That's where big players often buy, 
scooping up all the sell orders. 

240
00:22:51,520 --> 00:22:56,680
When the market is going down, look 
to sell just above recent highs. 

241
00:22:56,680 --> 00:23:01,720
That's where big players often 
sell into all the buy orders.
  

242
00:23:01,720 --> 00:23:09,000
For exits, think about where other traders might 
have their stop losses, or take profit orders. 

243
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:13,880
These create pools of liquidity.
As price approaches these areas,  

244
00:23:13,880 --> 00:23:17,840
be ready to exit your trade.
The price might reverse once  

245
00:23:17,840 --> 00:23:22,520
it hits these liquidity pools.
 
Every time the market makes a  

246
00:23:22,520 --> 00:23:27,840
new range, mark the high and low.
If you're trading in this range,  

247
00:23:27,840 --> 00:23:33,920
you might enter at one end (where there's 
internal liquidity) and exit at the other  

248
00:23:33,920 --> 00:23:40,360
end (where there's external liquidity).
Also, you want to trade where there's low  

249
00:23:40,360 --> 00:23:46,880
resistance. This means there should be little 
stopping for the price to move in your favor. 
  

250
00:23:46,880 --> 00:23:53,280
Start on a bigger timeframe, like the 
daily chart. Mark major liquidity levels.
  

251
00:23:53,280 --> 00:23:58,440
Move down to a smaller timeframe, 
like the 1-hour chart. Look for price  

252
00:23:58,440 --> 00:24:04,200
approaching your marked liquidity levels.
As price gets close to a liquidity level,  

253
00:24:04,200 --> 00:24:09,000
switch to an even smaller timeframe, 
like the 15-minute chart.
  

254
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:15,240
Watch for signs of a stop hunt – a quick spike 
through the level, followed by a reversal. 

255
00:24:15,240 --> 00:24:20,760
If you see this, get ready to enter a 
trade, in the direction of the reversal.

256
00:24:20,760 --> 00:24:26,120
Also, don't jump on every breakout. Wait 
for the price to show it's really going  

257
00:24:26,120 --> 00:24:32,000
to keep moving in that direction.
 
Always consult multiple time frames:  

258
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:38,840
check larger time frames to see if a move fits 
the bigger picture or if it might be inducement. 

259
00:24:38,840 --> 00:24:45,800
If you see the price quickly reject a level after 
breaking it, be ready for a possible reversal. 

260
00:24:45,800 --> 00:24:52,683
And don't put your stops right at obvious 
levels. That's where inducement often targets.
 
  

261
00:24:52,683 --> 00:24:54,840
Tools/indicators to analyze liquidity
There are several tools and indicators  

262
00:24:54,840 --> 00:24:58,320
that can help you spot and 
analyze liquidity in the markets. 

263
00:24:59,080 --> 00:25:04,800
First one, volume: This is one of the 
simplest and most effective tools. 

264
00:25:04,800 --> 00:25:08,400
High volume often shows high liquidity. 

265
00:25:08,400 --> 00:25:13,280
So look for volume spikes, which 
can indicate liquidity events.
  

266
00:25:13,280 --> 00:25:20,440
Second, Market Depth Charts. These show pending 
buy and sell orders at different price levels. 

267
00:25:20,440 --> 00:25:24,520
They can help you see where 
liquidity pools might be forming.
  

268
00:25:24,520 --> 00:25:31,320
Third, Time and Sales (or Tape Reading): 
This shows real-time trades. Large trades  

269
00:25:31,320 --> 00:25:36,440
or clusters of trades at certain 
prices can indicate liquidity.
 

270
00:25:36,440 --> 00:25:41,520
Fourth, Order Flow Indicators: These 
advanced tools try to show the balance  

271
00:25:41,520 --> 00:25:47,440
of buying and selling pressure. 
 
 
And fifth, Volume Profile: This shows  

272
00:25:47,440 --> 00:25:54,640
where most trading has happened at different price 
levels, helping identify high-liquidity zones. 
  

273
00:25:54,640 --> 00:26:01,440
It's best to use a mix of tools, and combine 
them with market structure and price action. 

274
00:26:01,440 --> 00:26:08,520
Also, these tools don't directly show "liquidity." 
They show things that often relate to liquidity. 

275
00:26:08,520 --> 00:26:12,360
You still need to interpret 
what they're telling you.
 
  

276
00:26:12,360 --> 00:26:14,606
Liquidity and order flow analysis

277
00:26:14,606 --> 00:26:16,240
Liquidity and order flow 
analysis are closely linked. 

278
00:26:16,240 --> 00:26:22,880
Order flow analysis is all about understanding 
the buying and selling pressure in the market. 

279
00:26:22,880 --> 00:26:29,320
This pressure often shows up as liquidity.
 
 
Order flow analysis looks at the actual orders  

280
00:26:29,320 --> 00:26:32,560
coming into the market.
It tries to spot where  

281
00:26:32,560 --> 00:26:38,760
big players are buying or selling.
Basically, order flow analysis can help  

282
00:26:38,760 --> 00:26:45,240
you find where liquidity is building up, when 
liquidity is being used up, and potential price  

283
00:26:45,240 --> 00:26:51,640
levels where big players might be active.
 
In order flow analysis, you need to get  

284
00:26:51,640 --> 00:26:57,040
familiar with several concepts.
First one, volume clusters:  

285
00:26:57,040 --> 00:27:02,800
order flow analysis often looks for 
clusters of orders at certain prices.  

286
00:27:02,800 --> 00:27:09,440
These clusters are actually liquidity pools.
 
Next concept is “absorption”: When a price  

287
00:27:09,440 --> 00:27:16,880
level "absorbs" a lot of orders without moving 
much, it's often a sign of high liquidity. 
  

288
00:27:16,880 --> 00:27:23,800
Here’s a familiar concept, imbalances: Order 
flow tools might show imbalances between buy  

289
00:27:23,800 --> 00:27:28,160
and sell orders. These imbalances 
can create or drain liquidity. 

290
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:33,493
It’s a lot to talk about, that’s 
a topic for another video.
 
  

291
00:27:33,493 --> 00:27:33,560
How to use liquidity analysis to 
compete with institutional traders

292
00:27:33,560 --> 00:27:39,640
Retail traders like you and me, can level the 
playing field by using liquidity analysis to  

293
00:27:39,640 --> 00:27:43,560
compete with institutional traders.
Here's how: 

294
00:27:43,560 --> 00:27:49,160
Know the closest liquidity pools. Mark 
the areas where lots of buy or sell  

295
00:27:49,160 --> 00:27:56,480
orders cluster. When price hits these spots, 
it often bounces or breaks through fast. You  

296
00:27:56,480 --> 00:28:02,640
need to be ready for both scenarios.
 
Watch for traps and liquidity sweeps.  

297
00:28:02,640 --> 00:28:07,800
Big players set traps to trick small 
traders. They often push price to key  

298
00:28:07,800 --> 00:28:15,080
levels. Don't fall for these fake-outs. 
 
Use multiple timeframes. Check both higher  

299
00:28:15,080 --> 00:28:20,480
and lower timeframes. This gives you a 
fuller picture of liquidity across different  

300
00:28:20,480 --> 00:28:27,360
market views. It helps you spot potential 
reversals or continuations more accurately.
 

301
00:28:27,360 --> 00:28:33,520
Track order flow. Pay attention to how orders 
are coming in. Look for big buy or sell walls  

302
00:28:33,520 --> 00:28:39,160
in the order book. These can signal where 
institutions are placing their orders.
  

303
00:28:39,160 --> 00:28:45,040
Identify liquidity gaps. These are areas 
on the chart with little trading activity.  

304
00:28:45,040 --> 00:28:50,160
Price often moves quickly through these 
zones. Knowing where they are can help  

305
00:28:50,160 --> 00:28:56,440
you set better entry and exit points.
 
Study market structure. Look for key  

306
00:28:56,440 --> 00:29:02,320
swing highs and lows. These often 
mark areas of high liquidity.
  

307
00:29:02,320 --> 00:29:08,000
Focus on session overlaps. When major 
trading sessions overlap, liquidity tends  

308
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:15,097
to increase. This can lead to bigger price 
moves. Use these times to your advantage.
 

309
00:29:15,097 --> 00:29:19,960
Don't chase breakouts. Many traders jump 
on breakouts, only to get burned. Instead,  

310
00:29:19,960 --> 00:29:27,720
look for pullbacks to liquidity zones, after a 
breakout. This is often where smart money enters.
  

311
00:29:27,720 --> 00:29:33,720
Use volume profile. This tool shows you 
where the most trading has happened at  

312
00:29:33,720 --> 00:29:39,920
different price levels. High volume nodes 
often act as strong liquidity areas. 

313
00:29:39,920 --> 00:29:43,000
Now, if you want to learn 
other smart money tactics,  

314
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:54,000
you need to watch one of these videos next.

